64. Mutat terra vices: taken from Hor. carm. 4. 7. 3. Cf. also 65—66 with 1—2 of the same ode: Diffuyere nives, redeunt iam qramina campis, Arboribusque comae. See note on 43, where this ode of Horace was imitated. alumni temporis = spring. According to the Thesaurus, alumnus with active meaning is quite common, e. g. Mart. 12. 60 ,1 Martis alumne dies. Auson. 381. 7-8 Hoc numero mensisque Numae redit, autumnique Principium referens Bacchi September alumnus. Isid. Oriy. 10. 3 et qui alit et alitur alumnus dici potest. alumni . . . auras: cf. Lucr. 1. 10—11 Nam simul ac species patefactast verna diei, Et reserata viqet genitalibus aura favoni.

66. vitreas . . . comas: of the grain bound into sheaves. Vitreas refers to the brilliant semi-transparent appearance of the ripe grain. This ad- iective is frequently applied to water, in the sense of clear or shjning. Both herba and coma are often used of grain, e. g.

Verg. Georq. 1. 134 sulcis frumenti quaereret herbam. Prop. 4. 2. 14 Et coma lactenti spicea sruye tumet.
